<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910826-0119</DOCNO><DOCID>910826-0119.</DOCID><HL>   BTR Plans to Buy   Rockware in an Offer   Totaling $324 Million   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5C</SO><CO>   U.BTR U.ROK</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)CONTAINERS andamp; PACKAGING, BAGS, CANS, BOXES (CTR)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>EUROPE (EU)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   LONDON -- BTR PLC, the British industrial holding company,said it agreed to acquire Rockware Group PLC, the packagingand printing concern in a friendly offer of #197.2 million($324.1 million).   BTR said the acquisition would be aimed at complementingits global packaging activities, especially in the area ofglass containers.</LP><TEXT>   Terms of the offer include a per-share price of 103 pence,representing a premium of 75% over the group's Thursdayclosing price of 59 pence a share on London's InternationalStock Exchange. BTR is also offering a share-swap alternativein which one new BTR share will be offered for every fourRockware ordinary shares and 11 new BTR shares will beoffered for every 35 Rockware convertible preference shares.A loan note alternative also is being offered.   BTR is one of Britain's biggest industrial holdingcompanies, with 1990 pretax profit of #966 million onturnover of #6.7 billion. Rockware's principal businesses arein glass, metal and plastic packaging as well as glasscrystals and business-form printing. It had pretax profit of#9.2 million in 1990 on sales of #243.4 million.</TEXT></DOC>